post_cb({"19079447": {"Id": "19079447", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>When a finite value of floating type is converted to an integer type, the fractional part is discarded (i.e., the value is <strong>truncated toward zero</strong>).</p>\n<p>So in the case of <code>-10.5</code>, it's converted to <code>-10</code>.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<h3>C++11 4.9 Floating-integral conversions [conv.fpint]</h3>\n<p id=\"so_19079290_19079447_0\">An rvalue of a floating point type can be converted to an rvalue of an integer type. The conversion truncates; that is, the fractional part is discarded. The behavior is undefined if the truncated value cannot be represented in the destination type. [ Note: If the destination type is bool, see 4.12. \u2014end note ]</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-29T14:55:41.513", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-09-29T14:55:41.513", "ParentId": "19079290", "Score": "8", "OwnerUserId": "1009479"}, "19079323": {"Id": "19079323", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>When converted to integers, the fractional part of the float is dropped, meaning the float 10.5 will be converted to the integer 10, and the float -10.5 will be converted to the integer -10.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "1403643", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-29T15:31:43.420", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-09-29T14:42:07.307", "ParentId": "19079290", "CommentCount": "5", "OwnerUserId": "1403643", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-29T15:31:43.420"}, "19079297": {"Id": "19079297", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The rule is quite simple: the number simply gets truncated to its integral part, in this case, to <code>10</code>. The fractional part gets dropped entirely. The same applies to negative numbers: <code>-10.5</code> would be converted to <code>-10</code>.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "661519", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-29T14:54:12.117", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2013-09-29T14:40:19.740", "ParentId": "19079290", "CommentCount": "4", "OwnerUserId": "661519", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-29T14:54:12.117"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_19079290_19079447_0": {"length": 24, "quality": 0.75, "section_id": 37}}, "n3337": {"so_19079290_19079447_0": {"length": 24, "quality": 0.75, "section_id": 34}}, "n4659": {"so_19079290_19079447_0": {"length": 22, "quality": 0.6875, "section_id": 37}}}, "19079290": {"ViewCount": "418", "Body": "<p>If I have </p>\n<pre><code>(float)value = 10.50\n</code></pre>\n<p>and do</p>\n<pre><code>int new_value = (int)value\n</code></pre>\n<p>what rules will round number?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "19079447", "Title": "How does Float round when converting it into integer", "CreationDate": "2013-09-29T14:39:40.737", "Id": "19079290", "CommentCount": "0", "FavoriteCount": "1", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-29T14:59:16.093", "LastEditorUserId": "1009479", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-29T15:31:43.420", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "2762231", "Tags": "<c++><floating-point><integer>", "AnswerCount": "3"}});